  "prompt": "Knighthood: Is it possible for a non-native British citizen to be knighted?",
  "response": "Yes, it is possible for a non-native British citizen to be knighted. The honor of knighthood, which is typically conferred as part of the British honours system, can be awarded to individuals who have made significant contributions in various fields, such as arts, sciences, public service, and more, regardless of their nationality. \n\nNon-British citizens who have made exceptional contributions may be considered for honorary knighthood. Honorary knights do not have the same rights as native British knights and typically do not receive the title \"Sir\" unless they become British citizens. Some notable examples of honorary knights include individuals from other countries who have had a significant impact on the UK or contributed to UK interests.",
